note.body:
I just ran into this report (Totem): https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/totem/-/issues/616, which seems very similar to this issue. 
They found that, as a workaround, you can use `GDK_GL=gles` to initialize it and videos would play fine. 
Unfortunately this doesn't seem to work for sushi. 

I'm a bit surprised there hasn't been more people affected/bother by this issue. For me, using sushi to preview video files had become second nature, frankly this has hindered my work flow since I started using wayland :disappointed:

target_title: Failed to initialized OpenGL with Gtk - Video playback issue (nVidia on Wayland)

note.body:
nVidia is known to not work properly on Wayland, even to this day. Recent news: https://www.phoronix.com/news/NVIDIA-Wayland-Roadmap-2024

You will have to wait for them to get their stuff sorted out, and hope that your device is recent enough to still be supported by their drivers. It is possible also that Sushi 48 might work better for you after the port to GTK4 and new video sinks.

target_title: sushi-media-bin: Fix llvmpipe detection

note.body:
I don't know if it's documented somewhere, but you can query the renderer strings used by the software renderers on any recent Linux distributions by using the `eglinfo` command:

```
$ env LIBGL_ALWAYS_SOFTWARE=1 GALLIUM_DRIVER=llvmpipe eglinfo -B -p surfaceless | sed -n 's/OpenGL core profile renderer: //p'
```
gives `llvmpipe (LLVM 18.1.8, 256 bits)`;

```
$ env LIBGL_ALWAYS_SOFTWARE=1 GALLIUM_DRIVER=softpipe eglinfo -B -p surfaceless | sed -n 's/OpenGL core profile renderer: //p'
```
gives `softpipe` for me.
